title: AWS Config Infrastructure and Partnership Reset
content: Inherited AWS Config with accumulated technical debt, unreliable stability/security, and strained relationships with partner teams. * Investment in Infrastructure: Explicitly prioritized foundational improvements in security, reliability, and partner integration features, despite short-term revenue impact. * Relationship Restoration: Led intensive reconciliation and trust-building efforts with partner teams. * Deep infrastructure expertise * Strategic prioritization * Inter-team conflict resolution * Stability improvements reduced production incidents by 70% within the first year. * Directly contributed critical infrastructure and features essential to successful AWS security flagship launch at re:Inforce.

title: Scaling AWS Organizations for Amazon Retail (SDO)
content: Amazon Retail (SDO), AWS's largest internal customer, required AWS Organizations to support unprecedented scale—initially far beyond the current capability. * Regular Deep-Dive Sessions: Conducted bi-weekly engineering deep-dive sessions with Amazon Retail, clearly communicating progress, roadblocks, and incremental feature releases. * Iterative Scaling and Testing: Guided systematic incremental feature releases, regularly validated by rigorous scalability and stress tests conducted jointly with SDO. * Deep technical scalability expertise * Persistent and transparent stakeholder engagement * Long-term strategic investment and execution * AWS Organizations usage scaled successfully to handle Amazon Retail’s massive multi-account footprint, becoming the governance backbone for an enterprise comprising thousands of accounts—now integrated into the core architecture. * Became only the second AWS service to graduate from high-level strategic oversight steering committees, a testament to the stability and scalability achieved.

title: Automated Reasoning (Weirwood) Integration into AWS Config
content: AWS Config had recurring stability and accuracy issues from human-authored governance controls—slow to develop and error-prone. * Technical Risk & Innovation: Decided strategically to reallocate engineers and budget toward integrating automated reasoning technology ("Weirwood") to write provably correct controls. * Investment Justification: Made explicit trade-off, prioritizing long-term gain over immediate technical debt remediation. * Strategic technical innovation * Bold decision-making under uncertainty * Ability to manage high-technical risk for outsized returns * Improved control development speed from ~60 days to ~2 days per control. * Doubled annual control-output capacity, significantly improving AWS Config’s operational reliability and customer trust.

title: JWCC Government Contract Turnaround
content: AWS discovered very late that a high-visibility JWCC (Joint Warfighter Cloud Capability) U.S. government contract bid faced failure due to a partner team committing to a non-viable third-party solution that couldn't deliver within required timelines. * Rapid Technical Re-architecting: Quickly engaged with the third-party vendor, negotiating modifications to their product to make it a feasible short-term hosted solution. * Strategic Negotiation: Reduced original cost by negotiating a new contract at approximately 1/6 the initial estimate, saving millions in projected expenses. * Proactive Transition Plan: Established a clear technical roadmap to smoothly transition to native AWS solutions post-initial delivery. * High-pressure negotiation skills * Crisis and risk management * Strategic flexibility and rapid innovation * Won the JWCC contract, avoiding reputational damage from public failure. * Successfully transitioned the customer to native AWS solutions at renewal, as customer feedback explicitly preferred AWS-managed solutions over third-party managed offerings.

title: AWS Config – Pricing and Positioning Pivot
content: When I took leadership of AWS Config, the prevailing internal narrative was that customer churn was due to pricing. The team and stakeholders were convinced we needed to significantly reduce prices. Inherited the Control Tower team focused incorrectly on recreating the full AWS user experience—resulting in complexity, delayed releases, and customer dissatisfaction. * Detailed Customer Segmentation Analysis: I initiated a deep usage-data study across customer segments. We examined churned and retained customer behaviors by analyzing service usage telemetry (retention rates, usage patterns, features accessed). * Customer Interviews & Price Testing: My team reached out directly to key churned customers. We explicitly tested the hypothesis by offering deeply discounted pricing (up to 50% off) to assess price sensitivity. * Feature Gap Analysis: Discovered through structured interviews that churned customers primarily sought specific inventory management features or capabilities from competitive services like Wiz, rather than lower costs. * Focused Value Proposition: Shifted strategy away from generalized AWS UI replication towards a focused, unique value—creating a centralized, reusable "Control Catalog." * Cross-team Collaboration: Worked closely with partner teams to identify common governance requirements, standardizing these controls centrally. * Analytical depth and rigor * Customer-centric research * Strategic decision-making backed by evidence * Clear strategic reframing * Cross-organizational alignment * Customer-focused value definition * After repositioning messaging around governance/audit rather than cost, we halted churn almost immediately and regained several key customers. * Internal data showed governance/audit customers had >85% retention rates, while churn was driven primarily by customers seeking specific missing inventory features. 📌 5. AWS Control Tower – Control Catalog Strategy * Reduced partner team duplication by over 60%, significantly accelerating adoption of Control Tower among large enterprise customers. * Customer satisfaction markedly increased, as evidenced by NPS improvement and direct positive feedback during AWS re:Invent and re:Inforce sessions.

title: Launching Foundational AWS Services
content: AWS Organizations: Launched in 2017; grew to manage governance for >90% AWS enterprise usage. AWS Service Quotas: Integrated with CloudWatch; significantly reduced service limit-related incidents. AWS Account Management: Enabled critical compliance workflows adopted broadly across AWS’s largest customers. AWS CloudWatch: Original launch; foundational for AWS observability at global scale. Internal Throttling Service: Protects global AWS infrastructure stability by enforcing usage limits reliably. title: Challenging Customer Relationship – Domain Controls
content: A major enterprise customer escalated severe frustrations around AWS governance practices, providing unclear and broad complaints, risking significant dissatisfaction and reputational damage. * Structured Customer Workshops: Facilitated detailed multi-day sessions mapping the customer’s current governance workflows and pain points, uncovering their core issue—absence of "domain controls," which prevented unauthorized account creation. * Strategic Customer Trust Building: Took the unusual step of transparently sharing our detailed roadmap, risks, and progress monthly, building trust and credibility over time. * High-level conflict resolution * Detailed process mapping and problem-solving * Exceptional stakeholder relationship management * After delivering the domain controls feature, the customer's sentiment dramatically improved, and they evolved into one of AWS’s closest and most trusted enterprise governance partners. * Their CIO later cited our transparency and engagement as a "model partnership" in internal communications, leading to smoother interactions on subsequent issues.

title: AWS Account Lifecycle and Deletion Integrity
content: AWS Account deletion compliance was initially split, causing hidden process gaps and significant compliance risks. * End-to-end Ownership: Consolidated responsibility fully into my team, removing ambiguity in accountability. * Incremental Technical Innovation: Developed a multi-source automated monitoring system to identify data deletion failures proactively. * Rigorous ownership * Incremental technical innovation and risk management * Accountability-driven leadership * Successfully deployed monitoring across hundreds of AWS services and thousands of internal systems. * Reduced compliance incidents substantially, proactively identifying dozens of data deletion gaps weekly—no major compliance events since implementation.

title: Bad hire
content:
**Situation:** The context of my worst senior hire was when I was leading a team with a strong technical outlook at Amazon. We were working on a product for organizations, and we were facing some challenges. Our customers were not familiar wit organizations, and our go-to-market strategy was not as effective as it could be. We were missing product experience and expertise in our team, and I was keen to balance the team with a product-focused person. 

**Task:** The task at hand was to hire a senior employee who could bring in the much-needed product experience. I interviewed a candidate who was looking to boomerang back to Amazon and had demonstrated strengths in product during the interview loop. However, there were two red flags that I noticed. The first was that the candidate had not left their previous team in good standing, and the second was that they were weak in tech. Despite these concerns, my manager, who was a bar raiser, felt that the candidate knew how to lean on their staff. I decided to take a calculated risk and hire this person, hoping that they could fill the product experience gap in our team.

**Action:** After the candidate was hired, they started off on a rough note. I noticed that they were not earning the team's trust, and several team members expressed their frustration to me. Initially, I attributed this to the usual bumps that come with a new hire settling in. However, the new hire did not improve as expected. They were not listening to or understanding the technical answers from the team. To address this, I took the step of coaching them myself and even set them up with a mentor who had successfully coached an underperformer before. Despite these efforts, the employee did not show any significant improvement. 

**Result:** Ultimately, I had to make the difficult decision to put the employee on a focus plan and eventually coach them out. I was transparent with them about their performance not meeting our expectations. This process ended up consuming more time than if I had not hired them at all, as I had to audit their work and provide quick and detailed feedback. In the end, after much coaching, the employee chose to leave on their own, although termination was imminent. From this experience, I learned that I should have paid more attention to the red flags during the hiring process. I was overconfident in my ability to coach someone through the technical details and took a risk that, in hindsight, I should have avoided. This experience has made me more cautious about taking such risks in the future, as they can lead to team burnout. If I could go back, I would not make the same decision again.

title: How do you balance operability vs. delivery speed at scale?
content:
**Situation:** At AWS, we were faced with a challenging situation with our AWS Config team. The architecture was in a disarray, we had discovered a host of security issues, and there were numerous features that we needed to roll out. The team was in a difficult position, and it was critical that we find the right balance between addressing these issues and continuing to deliver at a high speed. 

**Task:** My task was to guide the team in prioritizing their efforts and to ensure that we were maintaining our top three priorities: security, durability, and availability. I needed to help them understand the trade-offs we were willing to make to meet our customers' high expectations, without causing analysis paralysis or limiting their delivery. It was also crucial to address the technical debt and decide which aspects to fix first, without halting the team's progress for an extended period. 

**Action:** To achieve this, I held an offsite meeting with the top technical leaders and managers. We brainstormed our wish list of everything we could fix and discussed the impact of not addressing these issues. I conducted an exercise where I gave them 100 theoretical dollars to spend on the features, which helped us identify a system causing a cascading set of challenges. We decided to focus solely on fixing that technical component that year. In terms of features, I prioritized those that would help us achieve a more secure space. This led to the initiation of the Weirwood Project, which introduced automated reasoning. Despite being risky and initially met with skepticism, I explained the potential benefits and how we would decide early if it was working or not. I also ensured that the team was aware of the proof of concept created by a sister team and developed a roadmap with clear success metrics and check-in points. 

**Result:** Almost a year later, the Weirwood Project proved to be incredibly effective. We managed to reduce our rule creation timeline from three months to three days. More importantly, we reduced our security risks from 50 in a year to just half a dozen. This not only helped us maintain the trust of our customers but also allowed us to communicate clearly about our efforts to maintain a high security bar. The experience taught us the importance of clear prioritization, transparent communication about trade-offs, and the value of taking calculated risks. It also underscored the need for continual re-evaluation of investments and the power of finding projects that speed up delivery while reducing risks.

title: Simplifying Sign Up
content:
**Situation:** In my role as an owner of AWS accounts for several years, I was continually faced with customer feedback that the process of creating an AWS account was too complex. We also identified a high fraud risk due to customers' tendency to misuse EC2. Additionally, customers expressed a desire for a more scoped version of an account for testing purposes. They wanted an account that would allow them to start with just one thing for their development team. This feedback was consistent and recurring, and it was clear that a solution was needed.

**Task:** Every year, as part of our Obi-Wan process, we would collect potential projects. One recurring project was the concept of an account that was scoped down to a subset of AWS services. However, despite its recurrence, this project was always deemed 'below the line', meaning it was not considered worth the funding. The task was to find a way to bring this project to fruition, despite the lack of initial interest and the need for collaboration from our partner teams, particularly in payments and sign-up and sign-in.

**Action:** Despite the lack of initial interest, we documented the idea and shelved it for future consideration. While it wasn't a priority at the time, we recognized its potential value. This year, as part of a significant Gen AI push, there was a renewed focus on simplifying the AWS sign-up process. When concerns were raised by our partner teams, we were able to present our shelved solution as a potential answer. We had already thought through the general cost and knew which partners we would need to collaborate with. 

**Result:** This year, the business need for this solution became significant enough to justify the large, coordinated effort across many teams. We were able to secure rare banned funding to work on this simplified solution. The advantage was that we didn't have to spend time brainstorming potential solutions; we already had one ready. We had been listening to customer feedback, saw the trend, and finally had a good vehicle to deliver it by. We're currently working on delivery, and early testing shows that it benchmarks well in this space. We were able to get three teams across the organization invested in delivering this solution, which is now on track. This experience taught us the value of patience, persistence, and the importance of keeping good ideas on the back burner, even when they initially seem unfeasible.

title: Tracking a critical account deletion project
content:
**Situation:** In my role, I frequently find myself having to delegate mission-critical projects. One such instance that stands out was when we discovered an error in our process for deleting account information. This was a significant issue that required immediate attention and resolution. The challenge was two-fold: we had to address the existing gaps in our system and implement a new detection system to proactively identify such gaps in the future. 

**Task:** The task at hand was to not only rectify the current problem but also to ensure that such issues did not recur. To do this, we needed a comprehensive plan of action that included a clear understanding of the scope, a detailed plan, and a strategy to deal with any ambiguities. The end goal was to have a system in place that could efficiently detect and prevent such issues, thereby ensuring the integrity of our account deletion process.

**Action:** I delegated this mission-critical project to a strong leader within my team. We began by setting up a plan of action, which we reviewed with the team and my leaders to ensure everyone was on the same page. The leader then established a timeline and reprioritized resources, keeping me in the loop throughout the process. We decided to first focus all our resources on fixing the current issue. Once that was addressed, we moved on to implementing the detection mechanisms. To stay looped in, I requested weekly updates once the project was underway and daily email updates to monitor progress and identify any potential issues. I also made it clear to the leader that they should loop me in for quick escalation if they faced any roadblocks. Once we moved on to the detection and prevention phase, I switched to monthly updates but maintained the expectation for immediate escalation if needed.

**Result:** The result was successful execution and resolution of the problem at hand. We were able to fix the issues and track all the fixes. When we moved to the detection and prevention phase, I ensured that there were milestones no more than six weeks apart. This allowed me to keep a close eye on the progress and ensure that everything was on track. We also had a program-specific update in these monthly meetings, which provided an opportunity to dive deep, ask questions, and address any issues. This experience taught me the importance of having the right mechanisms in place to stay looped in on delegated projects and the value of clear communication and escalation paths in ensuring project success.
